Leishmaniasis, dogs - USA (05) 20000503094746
Date: 2 May 2000
From: Ezio Ferroglio <ferrogli@veter.unito.it>

We have faced a similar problem as reported about Leishmaniasis in dogs
(Canine Leishmaniasis, CanL) in Pennsylvania in North-West Italy at the
feet of the Alps. Cases of CanL were reported by colleagues from veterinary
cabinets in dogs that had never moved from the area.
Apparently no known vectors were present in an area more than 150 Km far
from the coastal zone where sand flies and CanL are reported. After 3
months of sand flies capture we found _Phlebotomus perniciosus_, a major
vector of CanL in Italy, in an area 7x8 Km wide.
It is very difficult to say if sand flies are autochthonous in the area or
are were accidentally introduced by humans activities. Has anyone
identified the species of _Leishmania_ involved in the outbreak? It would
be of great help to understand the source of infection and which species of
vector can be involved.
I suggest you test with the ELISA K39 all the dogs in the focus area and
you may want to start your search for sand flies immediately with the
coming of the warm weather. (Pennsylvania climatic conditions seems to be
similar to the one in North-West Italy, so you can expect to find sand
flies for the second half of June).
--
Ezio Ferroglio DVM PhD
Facolt√† di Medicina Veterinaria
Dipartimento di Produzioni Animali,
