[2
Date: 6 May 2000
From: Steve Grenard <grenard@con2.com>

_Leishmania donovani's_ life history is quite involved and host specific.
In the Indian epidemics, the particular sandflies (Silvery Sandly or
_Phlebotomus argentipes_) involved need to feed on a particular type of
nectar or fruit juice (raisins were used in the lab) to permit the
protozoan's life cycle to proceed.
It took 38 years to prove this with many false and embarassing trails (e.g.
bed bugs). There is a wonderful account of this in Dr Robert Desowitz's
book "The Malaria Capers" for those who may be interested.
One would think that the conditions must be absolutely on target for _L.
donovani_ to become established in sandflies in the US. In spite of this,
some veterinarians have suggested the disease could be brought to this
country by reptile intermediate hosts. In the absence of the right kinds of
flies and conditions, its jump to humans is not very likely or is it?
--
Steve Grenard
Staten Island University Hospital
grenard@con2.com
***
[3
Date: 4 May 2000
From: Paul Prociv <p.prociv@mailbox.uq.edu.au>

With all the discussion going on about leishmaniasis in dogs, wouldn't it
be reasonable to expect that, if the parasite were really there, and being
transmitted by sandflies, then there should also eventually be cases of
human infection? Or are there species/strains of _Leishmania_ which are
purely zoophilic?
--
Paul Prociv
p.prociv@mailbox.uq.edu.au
